title: Conflicts with FedEx, UPS & USPS apps.  Requires 3rd party scanner app
comment: The app is good for security, as it enables two factor authentication.  However, it does not work if the FedEx, UPS or USPS apps are installed.  Also, it requires the Barcode Scanner app from ZXing Team to scan QR codes.  The app definitely needs some work.  Setting up a new account by scanning a QR code does not work if the FedEx, UPS or USPS apps are installed.  The phone will try to scan the code with one of the shipping apps instead of the Google Authenticator app.  As a workaround, I removed all three apps, then scanned the QR code.  Authenticator then required installing another app, Barcode Scanner, from ZXing Team.  Note that the installation was required.  It didn't say "you need a scanner, pick one of these," it said "Barcode Scanner is required."  This makes things a real PITA.  If Barcode Scanner is required, then it should be installed at the time as Google Authenticator.  Also, the conflicts should be worked out between Authenticator / Barcode Scanner and other apps that have scanning capability (shipping, shopping, etc.).  If things worked like they should, the app would rate four or five stars.  Instead, I'm giving it two stars because it is such a pain.

title: If only I could back it up...
comment: Google Authenticator works great (though it seems to choke when using Google's own Goggles app?) Big fan of the app and 2-factor auth in general.  Unfortunately Google decided that we should not be able to back up Authenticator. Perhaps Google feels that, since they provide you with backup codes, you don't need to back up Authenticator, and I suspect that backing Authenticator up represents a security risk in itself.  Google needs to do a little Googling of their own as not all services offer backup codes and any risk associated with backing up Authenticator is the device owner's risk, not Googles.  As a result of Google's myopic decision upgrading your phone means breaking access to a number of services that offer 2-factor auth, or jumping though some very big hoops to disable 2-factor auth on all your accounts before proceeding with an upgrade, or forgoing the advantages of 2-factor auth where a provider does not offer backup codes.  3/5 for making me jump through unnecessary hoops.

title: User Beware
comment: This links your Google account to your phone number, so if someone steals your phone, you are locked out of your account permanently.   In addition, any device (phones, tablets, apps) which logs into your Google account needs to have it's own unique app-specific password (ASP) managed in Google account settings (this is basically MAC Filtering). Secure? Yes, it also allows you to remotely revoke permissions for certain devices.   However, this makes it incredibly easy to accidentally lock YOURSELF out of your own account, with no method of recovery. It's a lot like throwing away all the keys to your car, house & safe in favour of 1 tiny, un-copyable key, that causes your house, car & safe to explode in the event it goes missing.   If you are confident that you will never lose the key, 2-step verification is right for you. Otherwise, avoid it like the plague.

EDITED/SOLVED: Instead of using the barcode, select "enter provided key" in the app on the device, and select "can't scan barcode" on the website on your computer, then manually enter the long code with your existing account name, and it will work. title: If you have an Android, use 2FA
comment: Makes 2FA on your Google Account a no-brainer. I use to use the text messages to get my login codes, but the Authenticator makes it that much easier and more secure. Besides, it's called the Authenticator! The very name sounds like an Arnold Schwarzenegger movie! Great too that LastPass uses this app, got to get rid of my silly 2FA paper grid on that one. Here's a hint when moving to a new phone: keep your old phone (and Authenticator app) alive, then use the Browser Sign-in (three dots in the upper right) when setting up your Google account on your new Android. Use a code from your existing Authenticator app, then move it to the new phone using the web account portal for your Google account. Not the simplest thing, but good security rarely is!

This in turn asks yo to login via the web, where you need to enter your password again. So far, so good.  When you've done this, it prompts for the code generated by the app. When you hit the home/recent apps button, and then open the generator, the sign-in screen disappears and you're back at the initial sign-in request for re-authentication.
